GC.AST.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.def: Net acquisition of government financial assets includes domestic and foreign financial claims, SDRs, and gold bullion held by monetary authorities as a reserve asset. The net acquisition of financial assets should be offset by the net incurrence of liabilities.
GC.AST.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.name: Net acquisition of financial assets
GC.AST.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.AST.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.def: Net acquisition of government financial assets includes domestic and foreign financial claims, SDRs, and gold bullion held by monetary authorities as a reserve asset. The net acquisition of financial assets should be offset by the net incurrence of liabilities.
GC.AST.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.name: Net acquisition of financial assets
GC.AST.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.DOD.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.def: Debt is the entire stock of direct government fixed-term contractual obligations to others outstanding on a particular date. It includes domestic and foreign liabilities such as currency and money deposits, securities other than shares, and loans. It is the gross amount of government liabilities reduced by the amount of equity and financial derivatives held by the government. Because debt is a stock rather than a flow, it is measured as of a given date, usually the last day of the fiscal year.
GC.DOD.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.name: Central government debt
GC.DOD.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.DOD.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.def: Debt is the entire stock of direct government fixed-term contractual obligations to others outstanding on a particular date. It includes domestic and foreign liabilities such as currency and money deposits, securities other than shares, and loans. It is the gross amount of government liabilities reduced by the amount of equity and financial derivatives held by the government. Because debt is a stock rather than a flow, it is measured as of a given date, usually the last day of the fiscal year.
GC.DOD.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.name: Central government debt
GC.DOD.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.

GC.LBL.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.def: Net incurrence of government liabilities includes foreign financing (obtained from nonresidents) and domestic financing (obtained from residents), or the means by which a government provides financial resources to cover a budget deficit or allocates financial resources arising from a budget surplus. The net incurrence of liabilities should be offset by the net acquisition of financial assets.
GC.LBL.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.name: Net incurrence of liabilities
GC.LBL.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.LBL.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.def: Net incurrence of government liabilities includes foreign financing (obtained from nonresidents) and domestic financing (obtained from residents), or the means by which a government provides financial resources to cover a budget deficit or allocates financial resources arising from a budget surplus. The net incurrence of liabilities should be offset by the net acquisition of financial assets.
GC.LBL.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.name: Net incurrence of liabilities
GC.LBL.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.NFN.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.def: Net investment in government nonfinancial assets includes fixed assets, inventories, valuables, and nonproduced assets. Nonfinancial assets are stores of value and provide benefits either through their use in the production of goods and services or in the form of property income and holding gains. Net investment in nonfinancial assets also includes consumption of fixed capital.
GC.NFN.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.name: Net investment in nonfinancial assets
GC.NFN.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.NFN.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.def: Net investment in government nonfinancial assets includes fixed assets, inventories, valuables, and nonproduced assets. Nonfinancial assets are stores of value and provide benefits either through their use in the production of goods and services or in the form of property income and holding gains. Net investment in nonfinancial assets also includes consumption of fixed capital.
GC.NFN.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.name: Net investment in nonfinancial assets
GC.NFN.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.NLD.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.def: Net lending (+) / net borrowing (–) equals government revenue minus expense, minus net investment in nonfinancial assets. It is also equal to the net result of transactions in financial assets and liabilities. Net lending/net borrowing is a summary measure indicating the extent to which government is either putting financial resources at the disposal of other sectors in the economy or abroad, or utilizing the financial resources generated by other sectors in the economy or from abroad.
GC.NLD.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.name: Net lending
GC.NLD.TOTL.CN-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.

GC.NLD.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.def: Net lending (+) / net borrowing (–) equals government revenue minus expense, minus net investment in nonfinancial assets. It is also equal to the net result of transactions in financial assets and liabilities. Net lending/net borrowing is a summary measure indicating the extent to which government is either putting financial resources at the disposal of other sectors in the economy or abroad, or utilizing the financial resources generated by other sectors in the economy or from abroad.
GC.NLD.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.name: Net lending
GC.NLD.TOTL.GD.ZS-deficitFinancing.source: International Monetary Fund, Government Finance Statistics Yearbook and data files.
